335":"1335","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1310":"1310","about 1300":"circa 1300","1329":"1329","1306":"1306","Kingswinford St Mary, Staffordshire, England":"Kingswinford St Mary, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England":"Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1306–1335":"1306–1335","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1315–Male":"1315–Deceased","1329–1335":"1329–1335","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1332–1374":"1332–1374","1274–1348":"1274–1348","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","1374":"1374","1274":"1274","1260":"1260","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1310":"1310","about 1300":"about 1300","1329":"1329","1306":"1306","Kingswinford St Mary, Staffordshire, England":"Kingswinford St Mary, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England":"Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and English: nickname meaning ‘little crow, raven’, possibly applied to a black haired man, from Old French, Middle English <i>corbin</i>, a diminutive of <i>corb</i> ‘raven’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>corbin</i>, <i>corfbin</i> ‘crow, raven’).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the places in Calvados and Orne, France, named Corbon.","Irish: variant of   Corban  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carbin","meanings":["Swedish: soldier's name, from Swedish <i>karbin</i> ‘carbine’, a type of short rifle or musket used by cavalry.","Cornish: hypercorrect backformation from Cornish <i>carr-bons</i> ‘causeway’, or a habitational name from Carbis in Lelant (Cornwall), of the same derivation.","English: variant of   Corbin  ."]},{"name":"Corvin","meanings":["English (Durham): possibly a variant of   Corbin  .","Altered form of Scottish, Irish or English   Colvin  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Korving</b> (mainly The Hague): from the personal name <i>Korving</i>, from <i>Corvinus</i>, from Latin <i>corvus</i> ‘raven’."]},{"name":"Corban","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Corbáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corbán</i>’ or <b>Ó Coirbín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coirbín</i>’, both possibly from an occupational name based on <i>corb</i> ‘chariot’. Both names have also been Anglicized as   Corbett  .","Irish: alternatively, a variant of <b>Currivan</b>, from <b>Ó Coirbheáin</b>, itself a variant of   Corban   (pronounced with three syllables in Irish).","Romanian: nickname derived from <i>corb</i> ‘crow’, with the augmentative suffix <i>-an</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord William Thomas Corbin was born in 1306, in Kingswinford St Mary, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Corbin, was 32 and his mother, Felicia de Lutterly, was 46. He married Edith Frebody in 1325, in Birmingham, Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1335, in Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1306–1335":"1306–1335","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1329–1335":"1329–1335","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1332–1374":"1332–1374","1274–1348":"1274–1348","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1374":"1374","1274":"1274","1260":"1260","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1310":"1310","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1329":"1329","1306":"1306","Kingswinford St Mary, Staffordshire, England":"Kingswinford St Mary, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England":"Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1306–1335":"1306–1335","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1329–1335":"1329–1335","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1332–1374":"1332–1374","1274–1348":"1274–1348","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1374":"1374","1274":"1274","1260":"1260","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1310":"1310","about 1300":"noin 1300","1329":"1329","1306":"1306","Kingswinford St Mary, Staffordshire, England":"Kingswinford St Mary, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kingswinford, Staffordshire, England":"Kingswinford, Staffordshire, Engla